\begin{align*}
10b+a &= 20a+2b+7 \\
9b-19a &= 7 \\
\end{align*}

We know that $a+b=11$, so we can solve this system of equations using substitution. Solving for $b$ gives $b=19a/9-7/9$, which means $a$ must be a multiple of 9 between 1 and 9. Trying out each possible value of $a$ shows that $a=2$ is the only one that works, since $b$ must be a whole number. Therefore, $a=2$ and $b=9$, and the original number is $10a+b = \boxed{29}$.
